    "index_reference": "soothsayer",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<h1>SOOTHSAYER*</h1><p>One who foretells events; a pagan practice, soothsaying was forbidden in Israel (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut18:10,Deut18:14\">Dt 18:10, 14</a>). In Scripture, soothsaying was practiced by Balaam, Beor’s son (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh13:22\">Jos 13:22</a>) and King Manasseh of Judah (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs21:6\">2&nbsp;Kgs 21:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr33:6\">2&nbsp;Chr 33:6</a>); Jacob’s descendants were likened to the soothsayers of Philistia (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa2:6\">Is 2:6</a>); they were listed among the false prophets of Judah (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer27:9\">Jer 27:9</a>). During NT times, soothsaying was the source of a lucrative trade in Philippi (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:16\">Acts 16:16</a>).</p><p><em>See also</em> <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"6021\" data-resourceType=\"TyndaleBibleDictionary\">Magic</span>; <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"7749\" data-resourceType=\"TyndaleBibleDictionary\">Sorcery</span>.</p>",
